Name: Harriet Tubman
summary: Harriet Tubman was born into slavery around 1822 in Dorchester County, Maryland, and died on March 10, 1913. She became a renowned abolitionist and political activist, best known for leading enslaved people to freedom via the Underground Railroad as a 'conductor.' Tubman also served as a scout, spy, and nurse for the Union Army during the American Civil War, making her a key figure in U.S. military history. Her bravery and leadership cemented her legacy as one of the most influential figures in the fight against slavery and for civil rights.

Tubman died on March 10, 1913, in Auburn, New York, leaving a legacy as one of the most courageous and influential figures in American history.
